values.-1: I would prefer this is not merged as is

messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

So far it doesn't look safe. You should probably at least add Q_ASSERTs, otherwise I don't think we can sensibly hash anything or compare.

Patch Set 1:

> So far it doesn't look safe. You should probably at least add Q_ASSERTs, otherwise I don't think we can sensibly hash anything or compare.

What should I assert for? Both hash and comparison are done on the pointer, not on the T instance pointed to. The pointer is either null or given as argument to the ctor. If you give a factory, then you _also_ have to give a data pointer to the ctor. It won't create it for you. This is so that you can copy the deferred pointer around and have multiple copies refer to the same object, even before it's lazy loaded.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Given Andrei's confusion, maybe add your comment to the functions (we only care about the identity == address of the pointed to data, not about the actual value)

Patch Set 1:

I was thinking about QDeferredPointer(QSharedPointer<T>(), factory), which is probably how we want to use it. Afaiu, m_data.data() of such thing would be nullptr until we call lazyLoad(), so any operation on the m_data internals - before lazy load - would yield a different result from the same operation after lazy load, no?

Patch Set 1:

> I was thinking about QDeferredPointer(QSharedPointer<T>(), factory), which is probably how we want to use it. Afaiu, m_data.data() of such thing would be nullptr until we call lazyLoad(), so any operation on the m_data internals - before lazy load - would yield a different result from the same operation after lazy load, no?

Well, maybe the signature of the ctor is not quite optimal. You're not supposed to pass an empty QSharedPointer. You need to pass an object that's already allocated. It shouldn't be nullptr.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> > I was thinking about QDeferredPointer(QSharedPointer<T>(), factory), which is probably how we want to use it. Afaiu, m_data.data() of such thing would be nullptr until we call lazyLoad(), so any operation on the m_data internals - before lazy load - would yield a different result from the same operation after lazy load, no?
> 
> Well, maybe the signature of the ctor is not quite optimal. You're not supposed to pass an empty QSharedPointer. You need to pass an object that's already allocated. It shouldn't be nullptr.

Let's fix the API in a next step to get  things in before FF. Could you for now just add an assert that the pointer there is not null?

Patch Set 1:

> > I was thinking about QDeferredPointer(QSharedPointer<T>(), factory), which is probably how we want to use it. Afaiu, m_data.data() of such thing would be nullptr until we call lazyLoad(), so any operation on the m_data internals - before lazy load - would yield a different result from the same operation after lazy load, no?
> 
> Well, maybe the signature of the ctor is not quite optimal. You're not supposed to pass an empty QSharedPointer. You need to pass an object that's already allocated. It shouldn't be nullptr.

Okay, then let's fix this with an assertion. Not the best way, but it should hopefully prevent misusage.
(btw, why? I would've expected that case to be fairly nice to have)

Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

The assert actually hits

Patch Set 3:

> The assert actually hits

Yes, now that I think of it, it actually should. Otherwise you have no benefit of lazy loading.

Patch Set 3:

Well, okay, we can put dummy QQmlJSScope() inside.

Patch Set 3:

> Well, okay, we can put dummy QQmlJSScope() inside.

That's what we do. We allocate an empty QQmlJSScope, and populate it later. It still saves us all the parsing and type analysis.

Patch Set 3:

Where do we actually trigger the assert? Should we instead fix the callsite?

Patch Set 3:

The assert was triggered because I didn't consider the case of explicitly passing a null factory. It's fixed now.

messages.message:
Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2 Sanity-Review+1

Apparently pushing a Work In Progress

Patch Set 1:

Question: How should the overload set look in the end? As far as I can tell, we need
the const char *, qint64 overload for source compatibility and the QByteArray overload because it uses an optimized code path.
Thus QBAV has to necessarily use Q_WEAK_OVERLOAD.

I guess we could remove (with QT_REMOVED_SINCE) the const char * overload; not sure if that's worth the additional trouble though.

Patch Set 1:

Please include thinking about read() in your evaluations. If you're going to deprecate the pointer+size overload for write(), are you going to do the same for read()? And if so, what replaces it?

Patch Set 1:

> Question: How should the overload set look in the end?

- (const char*, qsizetype) // deprecated
- QByteArrayView
- Q_WEAK_OVERLOAD QByteArray

It's the expensive overload that needs to be weak, otherwise the (const char*) calls will be re-mapped to QByteArray(const char*) instead of QByteArrayView(const char*), causing the allocation and temporary object creation we want to avoid in caller code.

Patch Set 1:

I think so too. Even if we have a fast-path for QByteArray we would still have to construct it. And this fast-path is only applicable for the cases where _nothing_ from the QBA is written to the underlying stream, so in the normal case it would have to first allocate the QBA and then allocate a substring.

Patch Set 1:

> Please include thinking about read() in your evaluations.

Excellent point.

> If you're going to deprecate the pointer+size overload for write(), are you going to do the same for read()?

Can't, yet, because...

> And if so, what replaces it?

... that would be std::span<char/std::byte> (C++20).

So, we can deal with read() only once we depend on std::span's availability.
